## ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

### Key Breaking Changes

| Framework Pattern | Why It Breaks in Core | Core Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | No `ThreadAbortException` — method doesn't exist | Return `IActionResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | No `endResponse` parameter, no `Thread.Abort` | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `Response.Clear/Write/AddHeader` | Buffered response model removed | Return typed `ActionResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code | Remove entirely |
| `btnExport_Click` (WebForms events) | No server-side event model | Controller actions + routes |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // POST /report/export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        // Return FileContentResult — replaces the entire
        // Clear/ContentType/AddHeader/Write/End sequence.
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);

        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
        // Framework: Response.End() threw ThreadAbortException after flushing.
        // Core: Returning IActionResult cleanly ends the response pipeline —
        //       no exception, no Thread.Abort, no try/catch needed.
    }

    // POST /report/process
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Process()
    {
        // Framework used Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true) which called
        // Thread.Abort to stop execution. Core redirects are just return values.
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch block is REMOVED — it is never thrown in
        // Core. Keeping it would silently swallow real exceptions if the code
        // is later refactored to use tasks that throw OperationCanceledException
        // (which some devs confuse with the old pattern).
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "ProcessRequest failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => /* ... */ "";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Code-after-redirect still executes**
```csharp
// FRAMEWORK — code after this never runs (Thread.Abort kills it)
Response.Redirect("/login", true);
DoSomethingDangerous(); // never reached

// CORE — this WILL execute if you forget to return
HttpContext.Response.Redirect("/login"); // does NOT stop execution
DoSomethingDangerous(); // RUNS! Security bug.

// FIX: always use "return Redirect()" from a controller action.
```

**2. Don't write to Response body directly then redirect**
```csharp
// BROKEN in Core — response already started, redirect throws
Response.WriteAsync("logging...");
return Redirect("/done"); // InvalidOperationException

// FIX: choose one — either write a body OR redirect, never both.
```

**3. Auth pattern replacement** — instead of manual `IsAuthenticated` checks, use the `[Authorize]` attribute:
```csharp
[Authorize]          // returns 401/redirects to login automatically
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult Process()
{
    // User is guaranteed authenticated here
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

**4. Large file exports** — for big reports, stream instead of buffering:
```csharp
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ExportLarge()
{
    return new FileCallbackResult("text/csv", "report.csv", async (stream, _) =>
    {
        await using var writer = new StreamWriter(stream);
        await foreach (var row in GenerateRowsAsync())
            await writer.WriteLineAsync(row);
    });
}
// You'd implement FileCallbackResult or use FileStreamResult with a real stream.
```

### Summary

The core mental model shift: **Framework used exceptions for flow control** (`Thread.Abort` on redirect/end). **Core uses return values.** Every `Response.Redirect` becomes `return Redirect()`, every `Response.Write` + `Response.End` becomes `return File()` or `return Content()`. Remove all `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks — they're dead code that masks bugs.
